Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

case called at 2:46pm. [MK]
Defendant Windy L Clement in court.  ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.  
Ms. Clement reports on her four contacts with area attorneys and the retainer amount information she was given. 
The Court finds that Ms. Clement is constitutionally indigent.  The Court appoints Attorney Steven Spear as counsel for Ms. Clement.
The Court adjourns the Initial Appearance.  The Court requires Ms. Clement to telephone Attorney Spear's office today. 
The Court clarifies that the Criminal Complaint was amended at the previous hearing so that the single count is now Count #1.  The Court is not requiring the State to file a written Amended Complaint.
